T1  - Money and the Stock Market
AU  - Friedman, Milton
Y1  - 1988/04/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261534
DO  - 10.1086/261534
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 221
EP  - 245
VL  - 96
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Quarterly data for the period from 1961 to 1986 suggest that the real quantity of money (defined as M2) demanded relative to income is positively related to the deflated price of equities (Standard and Poor's composite) three quarters earlier and negatively related to the contemporaneous real stock price. The positive relation appears to reflect a wealth effect; the negative, a substitution effect. The wealth effect appears stronger than the substitution effect. The volume of transactions has an appreciable effect on M1 velocity but not on M2 velocity. Annual data for a century suggest that the apparent dominance of the wealth effect is the exception, not the rule.
AB  - Quarterly data for the period from 1961 to 1986 suggest that the real quantity of money (defined as M2) demanded relative to income is positively related to the deflated price of equities (Standard and Poor's composite) three quarters earlier and negatively related to the contemporaneous real stock price. The positive relation appears to reflect a wealth effect; the negative, a substitution effect. The wealth effect appears stronger than the substitution effect. The volume of transactions has an appreciable effect on M1 velocity but not on M2 velocity. Annual data for a century suggest that the apparent dominance of the wealth effect is the exception, not the rule.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261534
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261534
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Permanent and Temporary Components of Stock Prices
AU  - Fama, Eugene F.
AU  - French, Kenneth R.
Y1  - 1988/04/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261535
DO  - 10.1086/261535
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 246
EP  - 273
VL  - 96
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A slowly mean-reverting component of stock prices tends to induce negative autocorrelation in returns. The autocorrelation is weak for the daily and weekly holding periods common in market efficiency tests but stronger for long-horizon returns. In tests for the 1926-85 period, large negative autocorrelations for return horizons beyond a year suggest that predictable price variation due to mean reversion accounts for large fractions of 3-5-year return variances. Predictable variation is estimated to be about 40 percent of 3-5-year return variances for portfolios of small firms. The percentage falls to around 25 percent for portfolios of large firms.
AB  - A slowly mean-reverting component of stock prices tends to induce negative autocorrelation in returns. The autocorrelation is weak for the daily and weekly holding periods common in market efficiency tests but stronger for long-horizon returns. In tests for the 1926-85 period, large negative autocorrelations for return horizons beyond a year suggest that predictable price variation due to mean reversion accounts for large fractions of 3-5-year return variances. Predictable variation is estimated to be about 40 percent of 3-5-year return variances for portfolios of small firms. The percentage falls to around 25 percent for portfolios of large firms.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261535
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261535
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Mathematical Vindication of Ricardo on Machinery
AU  - Samuelson, Paul A.
Y1  - 1988/04/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261536
DO  - 10.1086/261536
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 274
EP  - 282
VL  - 96
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Ricardo is shown to be right that machinery can hurt wages and reduce output. A dramatic robot example reveals Wicksell's error in believing that Pareto optimality calls for no drop in total output from a viable invention. Under Ricardo's axiom that labor supply adjusts to keep wages at the subsistence level, he can correctly deduce on a market-clearing basis a rise in his net product (rent plus interest), while the greater drop in population and total wages result in a reduction in his gross product (rent plus interest plus wages).
AB  - Ricardo is shown to be right that machinery can hurt wages and reduce output. A dramatic robot example reveals Wicksell's error in believing that Pareto optimality calls for no drop in total output from a viable invention. Under Ricardo's axiom that labor supply adjusts to keep wages at the subsistence level, he can correctly deduce on a market-clearing basis a rise in his net product (rent plus interest), while the greater drop in population and total wages result in a reduction in his gross product (rent plus interest plus wages).
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261536
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261536
Y2  - 2024/03/22
